      <unit unitid="SubSecSpan">
         <titles>
            <title>The Span of a Set of Vectors</title>
            <plain.title>Span</plain.title>
         </titles>
         <body>
            <block>
               <block.body>
                  <def type="Definition" id="Def_Span">
                     <caption>Span</caption>
                     <associate type="Example">
                        <showme.pack.ref showmePackID="Exa_Span"/>
                        <info>
                           <info.caption>Example</info.caption>
                           <para>
                              <para.body>Examples of the span operation</para.body>
                           </para>
                        </info>
                     </associate>
                     <def.body>
                        <para>
                           <para.body>The span of a set of vectors <math>
                                 <latex>S</latex>
                              </math> in <math>
                                 <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
                              </math> is <math>
                                 <latex>\span(S)</latex>
                              </math>, the collection of all linear combinations of vectors <math>
                                 <latex>\Vect{s}_1</latex>
                              </math>, ... , <math>
                                 <latex>\Vect{s}_r</latex>
                              </math> in <math>
                                 <latex>S</latex>
                              </math>. – The span of the empty set is, by definition, the vector space consisting of the origin alone.
					</para.body>
                           <index.symbol>
                              <symbol>
                                 <math>
                                    <latex>\span(S)</latex>
                                 </math>
                              </symbol>
                              <info>
                                 <para>
                                    <para.body>The span of a subset <math>
                                          <latex>S</latex>
                                       </math> in <math>
                                          <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
                                       </math>.</para.body>
                                 </para>
                              </info>
                           </index.symbol>
                           <index.glossary>
                              <term>span</term>
                              <info>
                                 <para>
                                    <para.body>The span of a set of vectors <math>
                                          <latex>S</latex>
                                       </math> in <math>
                                          <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
                                       </math> is <math>
                                          <latex>\span(S)</latex>
                                       </math>, the collection of all linear combinations of vectors in <math>
                                          <latex>S</latex>
                                       </math>. – Definition of the concept.</para.body>
                                 </para>
                              </info>
                           </index.glossary>
                        </para>
                     </def.body>
                  </def>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>The following proposition confirms that the spanning construction always yields a subvector space of <math>
                           <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
                        </math>.</para.body>
                  </para>
                  <xi:include xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" href="SpanGivesSubspace.xml"/>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>Examples of subspaces obtained by the span construction are the row space and the column space of a matrix.</para.body>
                  </para>
                  <def type="Definition" id="Def_RowColumnSpace">
                     <caption>Row space / column space</caption>
                     <associate type="Explanation">
                        <unit.ref unitId="Expla_RowColumnSpace"/>
                        <info>
                           <info.caption>Explanation</info.caption>
                           <para>
                              <para.body>Details on the row and column space of a matrix.</para.body>
                           </para>
                        </info>
                     </associate>
                     <def.body>
                        <para>
                           <para.body>Given an <math>
                                 <latex>(m,n)</latex>
                              </math>-matrix <math>
                                 <latex>\Mtrx{A}</latex>
                              </math> express it in terms of its row and columns vectors</para.body>
                        </para>
                        <math.display>
                           <latex>
					
\Mtrx{A} =
\left[
\begin{array}{ccc}
a_{11} &amp; \cdots &amp; a_{1n} \\
\vdots &amp; \ddots &amp; \vdots \\
a_{m1} &amp; \cdots &amp; a_{mn}
\end{array}
\right] = 
\left[
\begin{array}{c}
R_1 \\ \vdots \\ R_m
\end{array}
\right] = 
\left[
\begin{array}{ccc}
C_1 &amp; \dots &amp; C_n
\end{array}
\right]
					
					</latex>
                        </math.display>
                        <ul>
                           <li>
                              <para>
                                 <para.body>The row space of <math>
                                       <latex>\Mtrx{A}</latex>
                                    </math> is <math>
                                       <latex>\RowSp{\Mtrx{A}} := \span \Set{ R_1,\dots ,R_m }</latex>
                                    </math>.
						</para.body>
                                 <index.symbol>
                                    <symbol>
                                       <math>
                                          <latex>\RowSp{\Mtrx{A}}</latex>
                                       </math>
                                    </symbol>
                                    <info>
                                       <para>
                                          <para.body>The row space of an <math>
                                                <latex>(m,n)</latex>
                                             </math>-matrix <math>
                                                <latex>\Mtrx{A}</latex>
                                             </math> is the subspace of <math>
                                                <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
                                             </math> spanned by the row vectors of <math>
                                                <latex>\Mtrx{A}</latex>
                                             </math>.</para.body>
                                       </para>
                                    </info>
                                 </index.symbol>
                                 <index.glossary>
                                    <term>row space</term>
                                    <info>
                                       <para>
                                          <para.body>The row space of an <math>
                                                <latex>(m,n)</latex>
                                             </math>-matrix <math>
                                                <latex>\Mtrx{A}</latex>
                                             </math> is the subspace of <math>
                                                <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
                                             </math> spanned by the row vectors of <math>
                                                <latex>\Mtrx{A}</latex>
                                             </math>.</para.body>
                                       </para>
                                    </info>
                                 </index.glossary>
                              </para>
                           </li>
                           <li>
                              <para>
                                 <para.body>The column space of <math>
                                       <latex>\Mtrx{A}</latex>
                                    </math> is <math>
                                       <latex>\ColSp{\Mtrx{A}} := \span \Set{ C_1,\dots ,C_n }</latex>
                                    </math>.
						</para.body>
                                 <index.symbol>
                                    <symbol>
                                       <math>
                                          <latex>\ColSp{\Mtrx{A}}</latex>
                                       </math>
                                    </symbol>
                                    <info>
                                       <para>
                                          <para.body>The column space of an <math>
                                                <latex>(m,n)</latex>
                                             </math>-matrix <math>
                                                <latex>\Mtrx{A}</latex>
                                             </math> is the subspace of <math>
                                                <latex>\RNr[m]</latex>
                                             </math> spanned by the column vectors of <math>
                                                <latex>\Mtrx{A}</latex>
                                             </math>.</para.body>
                                       </para>
                                    </info>
                                 </index.symbol>
                                 <index.glossary>
                                    <term>row space</term>
                                    <info>
                                       <para>
                                          <para.body>The column space of an <math>
                                                <latex>(m,n)</latex>
                                             </math>-matrix <math>
                                                <latex>\Mtrx{A}</latex>
                                             </math> is the subspace of <math>
                                                <latex>\RNr[m]</latex>
                                             </math> spanned by the column vectors of <math>
                                                <latex>\Mtrx{A}</latex>
                                             </math>.</para.body>
                                       </para>
                                    </info>
                                 </index.glossary>
                              </para>
                           </li>
                        </ul>
                     </def.body>
                  </def>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>We will soon learn how to describe the row and column spaces of a matrix using the concept of ‘basis’. For now, here is an indication of the significance of the column space construction:</para.body>
                  </para>
                  <xi:include xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude"
                              href="ColumnSpaceLinearEq_Thm.xml"/>
                  <xi:include xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude"
                              href="ColumnSpaceLinearMap_Thm.xml"/>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>Now consider two subsets <math>
                           <latex>S</latex>
                        </math> and <math>
                           <latex>T</latex>
                        </math> of <math>
                           <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
                        </math>. If <math>
                           <latex>S</latex>
                        </math> is a subset of <math>
                           <latex>T</latex>
                        </math>, how are <math>
                           <latex>\span(S)</latex>
                        </math> and <math>
                           <latex>\span(T)</latex>
                        </math> related? – The key to answering this question is ...</para.body>
                  </para>
                  <xi:include xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" href="SpanCompare_Thm.xml"/>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>We conclude this section with the following technical lemma about related spanning sets.</para.body>
                  </para>
                  <xi:include xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" href="SpanCompare1_Thm.xml"/>
               </block.body>
            </block>
         </body>
